The paper deals with graph partitioning, which is a fundamental problem in computer science and falls under the category of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The use of weights and capacities in the partitioning problem suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The problem of partitioning a graph into disjoint sets also has applications in computational geometry (cs.CG). The use of approximation algorithms and analysis of their performance suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of game theory (cs.GT) and computational complexity (cs.CC).
